AllLife Bank Customer Segmentation¶

Context¶

Over the next financial year, AllLife Bank wants to focus on its credit card customer base. The Marketing Research Team has advised that penetration in the market can be improved. Based on this, the Marketing Team proposes to run personalized campaigns to target new customers and also upsell to existing customers.

Another insight was that the customers have a poor perception of the bank's support services. Based on this, the Operations Team wants to upgrade the service delivery model, to ensure that customer queries are resolved more quickly.

Objective¶

  • Identify different segments among existing customers, based on their spending patterns as well as past interaction with the bank, using clustering algorithms
  • Provide recommendations to the bank on how to better market to and service these customers.

Methodology¶

  • For cross-marketing purposes, it may make sense to identify the cluster with the least amount of credit cards for marketing new credit cards.
  • It may also make sense to market credit cards to the cluster with the highest credit limit, since they will tend to have more money, and therefore be more desirable as clients.
  • For targeting new customers, it would make sense to find the cluster with the highest credit limit, and identify the most common method of contact for this cluster. The company should place a heavy emphasis on marketing using that contact method.
  • For improving service, it makes sense to find the largest cluster, identify their preferred method of contact, and focus on improving customer service for that method of contact.
  • It would also make sense to focus on improving customer service for the method of contact of the clients with the highest credit limit. We want to make a concerted effort to retain our most important clients.

# Function to create a combo boxplot/histogram with same x-axis.

def histogram_boxplot(data, feature, figsize=(12, 7), kde=False, bins=None):
    """
    Boxplot and histogram combined

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    figsize: size of figure (default (12,7))
    kde: whether to the show density curve (default False)
    bins: number of bins for histogram (default None)
    """
    f2, (ax_box2, ax_hist2) = plt.subplots(
        nrows=2,
        sharex=True,  # x-axis will be shared
        gridspec_kw={"height_ratios": (0.25, 0.75)},
        figsize=figsize,
    )  # creating 2 subplots
    sns.boxplot(
        data=data, x=feature, ax=ax_box2, showmeans=True, color="violet"
    )  # star on mean value of the column for the boxplot
    sns.histplot(
        data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2, bins=bins, palette="winter"
    ) if bins else sns.histplot(
        data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2
    )
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].mean(), color="green", linestyle="--"
    )  # Green line on mean for the histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].median(), color="black", linestyle="-"
    )  # Black line on median for the histogram

# Building a function to impute percentages into a bar plot
def bar_perc(plot, feature):
    total = len(feature) # length of the column
    for p in ax.patches:
        percentage = '{:.1f}%'.format(100 * p.get_height()/total)
        x = p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2 - 0.05
        y = p.get_y() + p.get_height()
        ax.annotate(percentage, (x, y), size = 12)

Clustering¶

  • I will try k-means clustering first, attempting with 2-9 clusters in a "for" loop, using Euclidean distances
  • I will find the best number of clusters using elbow method and silhouette score
  • Next, I will try hierarchical clustering, generate dendograms using several linkage methods, and find the best number of clusters using the dendograms and silhouette score
  • Finally, I will compare the best result from each method, and determine the best number and method of clustering
  • Since I only have 5 variables, I judge that it is not necessary to perform a feature extraction method like PCA
  • For all the above, I will use my scaled dataframe

K-Means Clustering¶

In [28]:
#Finding optimal no. of clusters

clusters=range(2,10)
meanDistortions=[]

for k in clusters:
    model=KMeans(n_clusters=k)
    model.fit(dfScaled)
    prediction=model.predict(dfScaled)
    meanDistortions.append(sum(np.min(cdist(dfScaled, model.cluster_centers_, 'euclidean'), axis=1)) / dfScaled.shape[0])


plt.plot(clusters, meanDistortions, 'bx-')
plt.xlabel('k')
plt.ylabel('Average distortion')
plt.title('Selecting k with the Elbow Method')

distance_metrics = ["euclidean", "chebyshev", "mahalanobis", "cityblock"]

high_cophenet_corr = 0
high_dm_lm = [0, 0]

# Nested for loop, running a model with all combinations of distance metrics 
# and linkage methods

for dm in distance_metrics:
    for lm in linkage_methods:
        Z = linkage(dfScaled, metric=dm, method=lm)
        c, coph_dists = cophenet(Z, pdist(dfScaled))
        print(
            "Cophenetic correlation for {} distance and {} linkage is {}.".format(
                dm.capitalize(), lm, c
            )
        )
        if high_cophenet_corr < c:
            high_cophenet_corr = c
            high_dm_lm[0] = dm
            high_dm_lm[1] = lm

# List of linkage methods

linkage_methods = ["average", "centroid", "weighted"]

# Lists to save results of cophenetic correlation calculation

compare_cols = ["Linkage", "Cophenetic Coefficient"]

# To create a subplot image

fig, axs = plt.subplots(len(linkage_methods), 1, figsize=(15, 30))

# We will enumerate through the list of linkage methods above
# For each linkage method, we will plot the dendrogram and calculate the cophenetic correlation

for i, method in enumerate(linkage_methods):
    Z = linkage(dfScaled, metric="euclidean", method=method)

    dendrogram(Z, ax=axs[i])
    axs[i].set_title(f"Dendrogram ({method.capitalize()} Linkage)")

    coph_corr, coph_dist = cophenet(Z, pdist(dfScaled))
    axs[i].annotate(
        f"Cophenetic\nCorrelation\n{coph_corr:0.2f}",
        (0.80, 0.80),
        xycoords="axes fraction",
    )

Comparing k-means to hierarchical¶

  • I will compare both results by answering the following questions:
    • Which clustering technique took less time for execution?
    • Which clustering technique gave you more distinct clusters?
    • How do the silhouette scores vary?
    • How many observations are there in the similar clusters of both algorithms?
    • How many clusters are obtained as the appropriate number of clusters from both algorithms?

Which clustering technique took less time for execution?¶

The answer is clearly k-means clustering. The code for hierarchical clustering took a bit longer to run, although not by much. Given the relatively small size of our dataframe, 660 x 660 distance comparisons in hierarchical wasn't that much more computationally expensive than 660 x 2-9 comparisons to centroid in k-means

Which clustering technique gave you more distinct clusters?¶

To answer this, I will re-visit the box plots for my best models.

Insights¶

  • Cluster 0: 224/660 clients
    • Lowest credit limit
    • Fewest credit cards
    • Preferred method of contacting the bank is to call
    • Clients in this cluster do make some use of online services.
    • Cluster is not fond of visiting the bank in person
  • Cluster 1 386/660 clients
    • Moderate credit limit
    • Moderate number of credit cards
    • Preferred method of contacting the bank is in person
    • Clients in this cluster make some use of phone services.
    • Cluster does not typically use online services.
  • Cluster 2 50/660 clients
    • Highest credit limit
    • Most credit cards
    • Preferred method of contacting the bank is online services.
    • Cluster does not make much use of in-person or phone services.

Recommendations¶

  • Cross-marketing to existing clients
    • Cluster 0 has the least number of credit cards with AllLife Bank. This group is also quite large. This is a largely untapped market for credit cards, and we should focus marketing credit cards to this cluster. While it is true that these clients have the lowest credit limits, what we lack in per-customer revenue, we can make up in volume of customers.
    • Cluster 2 has the highest credit limit. It only makes sense to target these clients for even more credit cards. This will not only increase the bottom line, it should also be effective in retaining these rich and important clients.
  • Targeting new clients
    • We want more than 50 clients with a high credit limit, so it makes sense to focus most of our marketing to new clients who would fit into cluster 2. This cluster prefers to use online services, so it only makes sense to focus our marketing on the internet, namely social media, video websites like YouTube, and the bank's website.
  • Improving customer service
    • The largest cluster is cluster 1. These clients prefer to visit the bank in-person, so it would make sense to improve our face-to-face interactions with clients, so that we meet the customer service needs of the most clients.
    • Cluster 2, representing our richest clients, is fond of using the internet for their servicing needs. Therefore, we should put a special emphasis on improving our online customer service, in order to retain our most important clients

Ideas for Future Research¶

  • In order to improve customer service, the bank should follow up a certain percentage of customer service interactions with a survey to determine specific areas that need improvement. We should include metrics such as rating the friendliness and knowledgability of the customer service representative, identifying how many contacts were required for the issue to be resolved, how likely the client would be to recommend us to a friend or family member, and overall satisfaction rating. It would be helpful if the answers could be in numeric form, to most easily translate into a regression model to determine the best ways to meet our client needs.
